{"by":"thinkingtoilet","id":47778578,"kids":[47779439,47778738,47779245],"parent":47740840,"text":"This is one of those times evolution doesn&#x27;t make sense to me. It&#x27;s clear how a giraffe&#x27;s neck evolves, the ones that could reach higher leaves in trees had an advantage. In examples like this, how does this evolve when there is no gradual change? An animal had to exist that had an offspring that somehow both absorbed the chloroplasts of the food it ate in a way that it could use (not just simple digestion), then have a place to store them, then have a mechanism to move the chloroplasts to the storage space, then have the mechanisms in their body to use the energy the stored chloroplasts create. How does that happen gradually when each step is totally useless without the others?<p>(please note I am not challenging the scientific truth of evolution, I simply do not understand how something like this happens)","time":1776259128,"type":"comment"}